<br>
If anything, by using terrorism - they have opened the lines for negotiation.  They have shown that they will not be bullied around by the West as they have been for decades.  They have demonstrated that they are not without teeth and should be treated as equals.  Their demands are very reasonable - the primary demand of the Islam world is for the West to stop interfering in their affairs.  The Great Satan, infidels, Jihad nonsense is just that: nonsense.  Nonsense that is used to trumpet up support.  I don't think it is unreasonable at all for the West to stop meddling in their business.<br>
<br>
How do you expect them to negotiate with the West on just terms when the West is constantly imposing their will upon them through military threats.  Any given country in the Middle East has no hope holding its own against U.S. in a conventional war.  So how do you expect them to negotiate while the hammer of U.S. military is constantly looming over their heads, making threats, making demands.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You speak as if we were the aggressors here. No matter which way you try to spin it, talking about Israel, troops in the Middle East, exerting influence, blah blah... (none of which I personally have a problem with anyway) ... they were the ones that decided to start murdering our people instead of negotiating or compromising. They can reap the whirlwind. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
YOU ARE THE AGGRESSORS!  Who is threatening to attack whom!?  You have been the aggressors for over 50 years in the Middle East!  When was the last time you have seen France, U.K., Germany or any other major Western country attacked by Muslim terrorists?  Now ask yourselves the question of whether those countries interfere in Middle Eastern affairs of their own volition.<br>
<br>
<br>
This whole Iraq charade has reached the point of utter ridiculousness.  It is an expected tangent of the War on Terrorism.  The WoT needs to be kept going in Bush's mind because as long as it does, the people of U.S. will be more inclined to put up with the bullshit of the Bush administration (Does anyone seriously think that the USA Patriot Bill could have been passed in the peacetime?).  So after the expected romp through Afghanistan, where to next?  Well, U.S. can keep pursuing Al-Qaeda and Bin laden (notice that media and the administration no longer even mention Bin laden and Al-Qaeda) but the victories in that are not clear cut and far fewer in between.  Chasing Al-Qaeda and Bin laden after the Afghanistan campaign would have proved detrimental to the Bush administration in terms of popular support.<br>
<br>
Think about it, Iraq isn't behind the 9/11 attacks, it had nothing to do with 9/11.  Saddam Hussein hates Osama Bin laden, but who is the next best target if Bin Laden is too slick for the CIA and the NSA?  Saddam of course, the favorite bad guy of the 1990's.  It is such a translucent joke.<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
As for Solovey.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Do you belive what has been done to Iraq is only justice for them taking the sovereignty of another nation?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Nope, that is ludicrous.  Two wrongs don't make a right.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Iraq Atacked kuwaite after all. We did not just point to it on a map and decide to start a war/ Place sanctions on them for the hell of it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If my memory serves me correctly, Kuwait pleaded to U.N. for assistance after being invaded.  Bush certainly took the call not out of the humanitarian reasons, but certainly because of oil and in hopes that the war would boost the stagnant economy in '91.  The correct course of action that would have been in the best interests of U.S. was to negotiate and abstain from armed conflict.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Of course many think they have already paid their dues, And been punished far too long for what they did. However, The same leader is still in power, Why should we trust him not to atack another country again.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If you feel so uncomfortable with him as the leader of Iraq, why did you not remove him when you had the chance?  Keeping a country and its people impoverished for over a decade is hardly a solution to your problem.  It obviously didn't stop him from trying to rebuild a defense force.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Why should we respect his sovreignty if he does not wish to respect other nations? Some people say it is our right, we did win the war. Others say no one has the right to control another people, which I can relate too.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Why should he respect your opinion on sovereignity when U.S. has the most violations of sovereignity than any other nation in the 20th century with the possible exception of Nazi Germany?  What exactly makes America an authority on this subject considering that it is questioning Saddam's ability to respect the sovereignity of other nations while simultaneously violating the sovereignity of his own state?<br>
<br>
You dont negotiate with someone at gunpoint.  That's not negotiations, that's extortion.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I understand there is more then just suddam in this picture, His people will also suffer. Its not an easy call by any means, But I am curious as to what you think we should do?<br>
<br>
you did say try talking to them like equals, Do you think someone like suddam can be reasoned with?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Of course he can be reasoned with.  He's not the evil madman dictator ruiding around on a camel as the Western media would have you believe.  The guy is smart, he knows how to wield power and how to maintain it.  Negotiating with him would go a long way towards improving the relations in Middle East instead of the idiotic saber rattling that is currently going on.<br>
